Index: row number for OD item when using a spreadsheet
Name: The User friendly name of OD can be used to link the OD to the code or component in O. using an extension in O.
Profile: The SD that this OD applies to, i.e., a lab numeric profile
unit: Unit(Coding) to apply to profile if is Quantity
allowedResults: allowedResults (Range|Code|Date):Permitted Range of values associated with code (text, Range, or valueSet depending on valueType) This is not part of O
RefRange: Reference Range 0..* associated with code and type, population and age (text, single value, Range, or valueSet depending on valueType) this is flattened out in this spreadsheet even though is nested in OD.
refType: Correspong RR type  in O this applies to - e.g.,Normal, Abnormaläó_
appliesTo: Corresponding population this applies to in O
refString: RR string value - only Range and string are represented in O
refLow: RR Range.low and RR Range.high unit string value - only Quantity and string are represented in O
refHigh: RR Range.low and RR Range.high unit string value - only Quantity and string are represented in O
interp: interpretation 0..* is a description of the logic to arrive at the interpretation, cam flatten out in spreadsheet to each applicable value.
interpDescription: text based description of how to get at particular interpretation.  This could also be code, CQL, fhirpath etc.
interpCode: the corresponding interpretation code in O (Hi|Lo|etc)
interpLowDecimal: the values that correspond to the interpretation code ( i.e. a name value = range pair ) this can be flattened out in a spreadsheet.   lowInterp[x](code|Coding|decimal|integer|string|Reference(ValueSet))
interpHighDecimal: the value that correspond to the high end of the interpretation code ( i.e. a name value= range pair ) this can be flattened out in a spreadsheet.   highInterp[x](code|Coding|decimal|integer|string|Reference(ValueSet))
